text: as a mom and person who has dealt with depression, anxiety and ptsd my whole life i know first hand that every day takes effort and sometimes choosing happiness isn't enough. depression and anxiety is a chemical imbalance! it's not made up or just in your head. you just can't snap out of it as some people may say. it takes work and sometimes takes medication and there is nothing wrong with taking medication if you need it.i see a counselor - i have taken medication and the mix of the two has helped me & counseling continues to help me but there is no quick fix -it is a process & healing takes time and work. some days are better than others and some people need to be on medication long term depending on what your dealing with. don't feel bad about your journey. no one is you. no one knows exactly how you feel. i'm not happy every day no one is- but we can not only survive it we can thrive through it! everything about you - everything that you are dealing with or have been through makes you who you are and that in it self is miraculous. we are all miracles. ‚ú® i am here to heal and in healing myself i hope to beable to help heal others so from one person dealing with mental health to another we got this‚úäÔ∏è

text:
thoughts of suicide are not foreign to me. i've been struggling with suicidal thoughts since i was four. i struggle with it everyday and there're forces that reinstate my worst conviction to end it all. 
last week, a dutch man referred to me and other pocs as diseases. he told me to kill myself. a week before that, a white woman grabbed my hair and a bunch of men harressed me because of my painted nails. but the worst forms come disguised as well wishers and as acquaintances with good intentions. they tend to dominate and belittle you and look for chances to demonize you to make them appear superior. 
what has worked for me is by removing such people from my life. it took me a while to understand that i don't owe anyone anything and that they've no liberty over me. i can't foresee and predict violence from strangers, but around acquaintances i can apply caution. 
it's a struggle to be me and easy to give up on life. but, i'm battling demons within me and around me.

text:
please get help if you're suicidal. please reachout to your loved one(s)if they're showing signs of suicidal tendencies. mental health is not a joke.

i suffered a small accident and the wound on my wrist had triggered thoughts of suicide. i keep wondering and wishing it to be a gash and so i could bleed to death and not exist. i'm struggling with casual racism and lgbtqi hate almost every day. i'm struggling with exam anxiety. i'm struggling with entitled and privileged people invading your safe spaces without warning and posing as well wishers, but in fact, they want to use you for their own personal agenda. i'm struggling to trust loved ones and it hurts. i'm struggling with financial problems. i'm struggling with loneliness. i'm struggling to stay happy. i'm struggling to eat and sleep. i'm struggling to put up a smile. i'm struggling not to pretend that i'm fine, but end up pretending anyway. i'm struggling with nightmares. i'm struggling with guilt. i'm struggling with shame. i'm struggling with fears of being violently confronted and sexually assaulted again. i'm struggling with fears of being mentally, physically and emotionally used and abused. i'm struggling with poverty. i'm struggling and it's exhausting. i feel the need to end it all. in struggling to live. 
so, i'm surrounding myself with lovely people minus all the toxic relations. i'm planning on making more art and workshops. i'm keeping myself busy and hunting for therapy. i'm getting help from wherever i can. i encourage you to do the same.

please get help. we're all worthy to live our lives. you're worthy to live your life. we deserve help. you deserve help. get help and reachout.

‚Ä™‚Äúhollywood's hijack of the #metoo movement‚Äù by @arightside ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Ä¨‚Äî
since actor amber heard‚Äôs 2016 domestic abuse allegations against her now ex-husband and actor johnny depp, her career has appeared to thrive even more. that hasn‚Äôt been the case for depp though. all the while, reports have surfaced which have challenged the truthfulness of heard‚Äôs allegations. depp has always maintained his innocence and just like his ex-wife, he‚Äôs had eyewitness support since the may 2016 alleged incident. unfortunately, depp has already been deemed guilty in the court of public opinion. that said, what movement is in place to support those who try to defend themselves in the court of public opinion? those who want due process?
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
here‚Äôs an excerpt from my column:
two domestic abuse-trained police who arrived on the scene soon after the alleged incident ‚Äî and who later gave sworn witness depositions ‚Äî as well as surveillance camera videotapes of heard's face and a growing group of witnesses who interacted closely with a makeup-free heard over the five ensuing days all agree that the injury she presented to the world wasn't legitimate. six perfect-face days after heard claimed depp beat her and "destroyed" his own penthouse apartment ‚Äî which police found in perfect condition ‚Äî she magically presented her battered face to trailing paparazzi and a judge who granted her an automatic temporary restraining order against depp. visit the link in my bio for the full story.

text: anita hill is an american attorney, author and professor. in 1991, during a senate confirmation hearing for u.s. supreme court justice clarence thomas, hill testified that he sexually harassed her for years in the workplace. her testimony was controversial in the pre #metoo era and thomas was narrowly confirmed. hill became a symbol of women's rights in the workplace, with @kerrywashington portraying her in the 2016 film "confirmation." last year, a new generation learned about anita hill, as it was impossible to ignore the parallels between her allegations against thomas and sexual assault allegations made by dr. christine blasey ford against supreme court justice brett kavanaugh during his confirmation hearings.

text:
cw: me too, depression, suicide attempt, healing
tomorrow is the 3 year anniversary of something that i will never erase from my mind, something i have had a hard time moving past. #metoo behind the announcer box on the football field, in both backrooms of the choir room, on a tour bus, and in an empty science lab pver the course of a year and a half. all by the same boy who i thought was a friend. no, i did not report it. i had the chance a few times, but i was never ready. i was beaten and broken down every time. i had nightmares constantly, we had the same friends, the same class, he sat but feet away from me. he was one of my best friends. combine that with(at the time)undiagnosed bipolar disorder and normal teenage issues you have quite a storm. i tried to date him because i thought if he had feelings then itd make me feel better somehow, that itd fix me... it didn't. it gave him more opportunity and just made things worse. i finally took the big step of cutting him off a few days after he assaulted me on a tour bus... but a few months after graduating i faced everything i was shoving down again. it hit me hard in the face, i had never been so depressed in my life. i felt like i was being pulled down deeper and deeper, but that it was wrong to tell anyone about it. that i had to stay happy and bubbly all the time, so i made a fantasy world in my head to escape to. needless to say it did not get any better, and on april 13th i admitted myself to the hospital after taking 33 tylenol. in the hospital i told my mom what was happening with me, and less than a month later i had found a therapist and was doing much better. i didnt think id make it this far, or that id ever be this happy. i didnt know love was as real as it is to me right now. i still have a ways to go, i still have triggers, just not as many...i still have nightmares but not as often or as intense..i still am anxious and paranoid about it but its not as bad..and i'm doing pretty okay. and i'm proud of that! so while i know not a ton of people will read this, i decided to publicly tell my story as a stepping stone for me. another step forward and towards happiness..to say things get better.
name: Katie Dawn Burgess

text: the term ‚Äúsex positive‚Äù has many interpretations. we believe it is having positive attitudes about sex and feeling comfortable with one‚Äôs own sexual identity, preferences and with the sexual behaviors of others. sex positive people often have the following traits (the most important is confidence and no shame): ‚Ä¢ they are open to learning about sex and healthy, pleasurable sexual activity. they try to understand their bodies, their partners‚Äô bodies, and all of the physical, emotional, and psychological elements involved with intimacy. they feel comfortable asking questions. ‚Ä¢ they value safe sex for themselves and for their partners. safe sex includes discussing sexual histories, using condoms, and being tested for sexually transmitted infections (stis). it is also emotional and psychological safety ‚Äî supporting a partner with a sexual dysfunction or one with a history of sexual trauma or abuse. ‚Ä¢ they believe sex is a healthy part of life to be enjoyed. sex is discussed without shame. it is not a taboo subject. ‚Ä¢ they acknowledge boundaries, consent, and the natural fact that sometimes they won‚Äôt want to have sex (and partners might not want to have sex with them). ‚Ä¢ they accept the sexual practices of others, as long as there is consent and safety (without judgment). this means accepting others‚Äô sexual orientations and lifestyles without judgment. being sex positive is understanding your own sexuality, pleasure, safety  and what it means for you and your relationships. #losangeles #consent #magicofpsalm #endsexualharassment #endsexualviolence #boundaries #safety #affirmativeconsent #sexed #endsextrafficking #metoo #timesup #sanfrancisco #sexpositive #education #empowerment #leadership

#mentoo people close to me know how much i love men. quite a few of my best friends are men (straight & gay). thru these relationships i have learned that men often feel pressure to live up to covert marketing standard of what it means to be a man. i believe that‚Äôs because of social engineering and propaganda a man‚Äôs divine purpose, which is to provide and protect for his family and community has been displaced and as a result it gives birth to toxic masculinity. we all need healing on both the masculine and feminine side. and let us not forget, every man is born of a wombman. so as wombmen, it‚Äôs important to chose the father of your children carefully. a man is more secure when he can stand on the shoulders of his forefathers.  even in the animal kingdom the female chooses her mate wisely and based on strength. if the female in the animal world is that careful, shouldn‚Äôt we as humans also.

in recent times, women are speaking out more and more about the violence they have endured at the hands of abusive men. the #metoo movement sparked much needed conversations around consent, trauma, and how to better relate to one another.

these are all necessary. however, it is vital that we remember that men are not born violent. as the headlines fill up day by day with story upon story of another powerful man held accountable for sexual violence or misconduct, it‚Äôs essential that we remember the true beauty of healthy male sexuality and energy.

text:
new york rep. shirley chisholm smiles as she's greeted by friendly faces and applause during the 1972 democratic national convention in miami beach, florida.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
born in 1924 in new york city, chisholm was the first african-american woman to be elected to congress, the first african-american to run for president (long before jesse jackson or barack obama) and the first woman to run for the democratic party's presidential nomination. chisholm's run proved unsuccessful, only winning a handful of delegates, but her journey proved an inspiration to millions of american women. perhaps she said it best herself, ""if they don't give you a seat at the table, bring a folding chair."‚†Ä
‚†Ä
| üì∏ image from bbc |‚†Ä
‚†Ä

text:
this piece is less about personal story than it is about the paradigm our society has operated within for the last couple thousand years. what is personal is the blunt manner i choose to depict the destruction of it. throughout history biblical salome and judith paintings have adorned the walls of the richest houses and are currently celebrated in the finest art museums around the world. i don‚Äôt dare compare myself to some of those masterful works, i only mean to credit inspiration and take it a step farther.
i love men. that love does not distract or scare me in the slightest from discussing real issues in my work. 
time to be brave. all of us. #metoo isn‚Äôt just a modern day movement, it‚Äôs an expression of the rejection of (for me) patriarchy and the sexual objectification and abuse of all humans. maybe through less subdued and polite means we can achieve the change we are so thirsty for. 
here‚Äôs a glass of water. drink.
üîÆ

time to be brave. all of us.  isn‚Äôt just a modern day movement, it‚Äôs an expression of the rejection of (for me) patriarchy and the sexual objectification and abuse of all humans. maybe through less subdued and polite means we can achieve the change we are so thirsty for. 
here‚Äôs a glass of water. drink.

text: i‚Äôm sitting here humbled by my journey. thinking of where i am now and where i came from. thinking of what it took to strip me to my core and get me to be my most vulnerable and authentic self. i‚Äôm here with the message that it‚Äôs not easy but it‚Äôs absolutely worth it..........the pain, fear, guilt, and shame can feel crippling at times. it freezes you from acting on behalf of your high self. while i thawed through this freeze my ego fought hard to keep me from rising up. i have had to let go of some people i thought would be in my life forever. i have made amazing soul connection with people i know will be in my life forever. i have lost and i have gained but i trust that everything i have lost will no longer serve me. i have taken back my power and my control. in doing all this i will end a cycle of ancestral and trans generational trauma and abuse. no matter who you are or where you came from i‚Äôm here to tell you that you can break the cycle too. if you don‚Äôt know where or how to start or if fear is holding you back just know that you are strong enough and that if you do the work things will get better. if you are ready to unfreeze and start to feel just know that i am here to listen.  #breakingthecycle #breakingthesilence #risingwoman #togetherwerise #riseup #healing #spiritualawakening #spirituality #higherconsciousness #higherself #selflove #talktome #eatingdisorderrecovery #metoo

text:
dante non fu il primo a fare cat√†basi (la discesa agli inferi). la fece ad esempio gi√† ulisse, dopo aver abbandonato la maga circe. giunse nel paese dei cimmeri ai confini dell'oceano, avvolto nella nebbia. ivi discese nel regno dei morti ove interrog√≤ l'indovino tiresia. incontr√≤ vari personaggi, tra cui la madre ed i grandi dannati (minosse, orione, tantalo, sisifo, eracle). manca una "topografia" dell'ade che avremo invece nell'eneide. l'eroe si arresta sulla soglia dove gli appaiono le ombre dei morti che lui invano cerca di abbracciare. hanno pur tuttavia grande vigore fisico (sisifo spinge un enorme masso). dante conosceva omero di fama o per via mediata, tramite compendi o commenti latini. i poemi omerici furono tradotti nell'epoca di petrarca e boccaccio.
nel "somnium scipionis" di cicerone (129 ante nostra era) nella villa di scipione emiliano, costui racconta il sogno fatto 20 anni prima dal nonno scipione l'africano. l'aldil√† qui √® posto nelle stelle, al centro della via lattea. cicerone si rif√† al mito di er della repubblica di platone. er, soldato ritenuto morto, sarebbe tornato in vita raccontando dell'oltretomba. il viaggio √® dato per reale da platone, ridotto allo status di sogno da cicerone. il 6¬∫ canto dell'eneide parla della discesa nell'averno. enea sbarca a cuma, consulta la sibilla e discende con lei negli inferi. ovidio parla del viaggio di orfeo per riportare euridice nel mondo dei vivi. il potere dell'arte non pu√≤ nulla sull'umana coglionaggine: egli si volta e non pu√≤ compiersi il ritorno alla vita di euridice. secondo alcune versioni egli rinuncia per sempre alle donne, secondo altre si rivolge ad amori omosessuali. la "visio sancti pauli" √® un testo greco tradotto in latino nel 500, tratti da un breve accenno della 2¬™ lettera ai corinzi. dante vi fa riferimento esplicito. san paolo viene rapito da un angelo e gli vengono mostrate le anime dei morti: incontrer√† profeti, patriarchi, santi e beati. quando compare il purgatorio per la prima volta nella narrazione? nel "purgatorio di san patrizio" di enrico di saltrey (12¬∫-13¬∫ secolo).

text:
i was speaking with a board member of a different nonprofit over lunch. he explained to me how his mother-in-law has a saying: ‚Äúhurt people hurt people.‚Äù it makes sense. and then, our newest writer [dharmanerd] said almost the same exact thing in her post about an emotionally abusive relationship. it‚Äôs pretty spot on. when we‚Äôre truly happy, we do our best to make the world a better place‚Äîand we‚Äôre not abusive.

so why do abusers abuse? there‚Äôs no clear-cut answer, but people who abuse their partners believe they have the right to control them. abuse is a learned behavior. sometimes abusers see it growing up and are never taught how to break the abusive cycle. other times, abusers learn from friends or pop culture. no matter how you learned it though, abuse is a choice.

psychology today says that most abusers have the following personality profile: insecure, needy, distrustful, jealous, verbally abusive, needs to be in control, possessive, hypersensitive, aggressive, blames others for their behavior, and suffers from untreated mental heal problems.

what do you think? do happy people abuse?

text:
my intention was to make this painting in one sitting and post it yesterday, to remind those without valentines that they are not forgotten, not alone and are loved (no matter their circumstances). üñ§

but, i didn‚Äôt make it in time cuz life happens, and sometimes i feel like i‚Äôm just late to the game, but really i just have to push my anxieties out of the way which makes me feel late. üñ§

so today!  the after after valentine‚Äôs day, the day after those of you coming off all your dopamine trips and the others who are finding cures for their loneliness. today! especially for you who feel unlovable, unseen and unknown, and alone, please know that is a big fat lie. üñ§

you are loved. 
you are loved. 
you are loved. üñ§

everyday. üñ§

ps:  there will be more of these little lovenotes.  the goal is to cover a large wall with them. üòÜüíå. #loved #lovenotes #painting #wordsmatter #youmatter #thisisapainting #wordart #acrylicpainting #metoo #lovenote #halfthestory #oktosay #hereforyou #lookforthehelpers #metoo #bethedifference #wagepeace #orangetheworld #wordsthatmatter #timesup #believesurvivors #seizetheawkward #artaesthetics

text:
i‚Äôve decided to share this because i think a lot of people have no idea how bad it is & what a massive role the media plays in deliberately fuelling misconceptions about feminism in order to attract ‚Äúcontroversy‚Äù and click bait. it‚Äôs particularly heartbreaking given the amount of time & energy we spend desperately trying to persuade the media to cover issues like sexual violence service funding, domestic violence statistics, period poverty, campus sexual violence, detention of refugee women, sex & relationships education, workplace sexual harassment etc. instead you‚Äôre asked to spend endless time and energy ‚Äúdebating‚Äù topics like these often against an extreme misogynist whose ideas are being given credibility and airtime in the hope of whipping up outrage against pc feminazis gone mad so the interview will go viral. it‚Äôs exhausting and frustrating.

it‚Äôs laminated with magnets glued to the back.

text:
i find my self standing in front of two pathways, again... the one that is all too familiar to stagger  down... the one that numbs the pain briefly by suffocating and filling the body with food until this body physically cannot hold anymore.

or, the one that at first feels cold, seems foggy, where no light shines until i‚Äôve taken a few, or a lot of steps down, it... and finally the sun rises.

as i stand, i take a deep breath.

i hold it.

and i say yes to the one that‚Äôs unfamiliar ground. again.

i‚Äôve said yes to the unfamiliar ground many times now before (to help me make peace with this eating behaviour)... but this time, i will not pretend, this path is one i am entering feeling afraid. 
i said no to it years ago, but now i have my own hand to hold, i know i can just about do it.

over the last several months i have felt the mother to crying parts of me blossom... but this mothering part of me, she is afraid herself... though as i fall to my knees on this unfamiliar path i hear me as mother speak softly as her trembling hands hold the child of me... and she says: ‚Äúdarling, it‚Äôs ok. you‚Äôre scared, and i am not so sure what to do right now either... but i can promise you, we will find out together. you are here, you are safe, and i have you now.

i see you. i feel you. i love you.

after everything you have been through alone, there is nothing, we cannot get through together.‚Äù ‚Äî

the journey of self transcendence, the journey of turning inwards is not always a magically soothing one with beans of sunlight and triple rainbows as it can be painted to be... ...it can feel uneasy, unwelcoming and cold... but i promise if you commit to you, 
you will get through,
every tiny hole in the wall,
every tiny crack,
will, with time, break open,
and there will be light,
and there will be love.

wherever you are, you have got this.
may these walls come tumbling down,
in the arms of love.

i love you.

text:
oeps, grapje.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
'geer wat doet u nou?'. zo sprak het internet vol afschuw over een video waarin te zien is hoe een man - of toch jongetje - vol overtuiging een zoen van gerard joling moet incasseren. hypocriet nederland viel er vol ongeloof overheen om gerard uit te maken voor 'vuillak', 'smeerlap' en 'klootzak'. zijn we goed in, en masse lekker kortzichtig scheldkanonnades over en weer gooien via het internet. lekker anoniem, niet nadenken en gewoon schreeuwen. de beste man kon ten tijde van de opgenomen video lachen met de situatie - zo zien we aan de beelden - maar daar denkt hij nu klaarblijkelijk anders over. sterker nog, hij denkt erover na om stappen te ondernemen ten opzichte van de heer joling. vreemd, je zou bijna denken dat alle betrokkenen wisten wat er zou gebeuren. of was die telefoon per ongeluk aan het filmen? oh nee, dat was voor die foto die de jongeman graag had gehad. grappig, men spreekt alweer over #metoo en gerard joling is de gebeten hond. 'wat als dit een vrouw was geweest?' - nou dan waren de rapen gaar kan ik jullie vertellen. mannen onder elkaar, lekker flauwekullen - lekker mannelijk doen. totdat het 't internet overgaat, dan slikken ze hun teelballen sneller in dan ze oorspronkelijk ingedaald waren. dan is 't niet meer stoer, ben je het pispaaltje. dat er vervolgens een hoop huismoeders en laaggeschoolden zich verplicht voelen om hun homohaat even de vrije loop te laten op social media, dat moeten we maar even voor lief nemen. nee gerard, jij bn'er, jij had beter moeten weten. slechts een kwestie van tijd alvorens we hier amerikaanse taferelen krijgen en jij, gerard, jij bankroet bent door een opname als deze. dat een stel onnozelen gerard andersom een beetje tot vervelende acties aanzetten, dat komt niet ter sprake natuurlijk. lekker hypocriet weer. de duistere kant van roem, vooral wanneer anderen ervan willen profiteren.

text: i‚Äôve been writing this over and over in my head but i‚Äôve just decided to write this from the heart, that way it‚Äôs genuine. this is the story about a time that didn‚Äôt almost break me, but a time that did break me. it was back in 2017, two years ago, but it still feels like just yesterday. i was sexually assaulted. you think it won‚Äôt happen to you...until it does. i was 18 but in that moment i didn‚Äôt know what to do. i felt so powerless and it took me a while to comprehend what had actually happened to me. that was the toughest year for me by far. i still worked out but it didn‚Äôt bring me joy like it used to. i worked out but ate my feelings. i worked out but didn‚Äôt feel like i deserved to look and feel healthy. i thought that if i made myself bigger and bigger that it would stop anybody from looking at me in a sexual manner. i blamed myself everyday for what happened and so i treated my body poorly. i gained at least 20-30 pounds during that point in my life and drove myself to my highest weight. the sad part was that it didn‚Äôt stop him or anybody else from looking at me sexually. all it did was hurt my health and make me depressed. it took me about a year to fully recover from the experience. i talked to friends and what really helped was that i talked to my world religions professor about it because we were opening up about something personal that had shaped us into the person that we are. we didn‚Äôt have to share it in front of everybody so i didn‚Äôt, but just him knowing and talking to me about it allowed me to free myself from the chains that i had put around myself. he was no longer controlling me but he was at the same time because i was doing all these horrible things to myself. that time in my life did break me, but i built myself back up, with the help of my best friend. i love working out now again, i‚Äôm stronger, i‚Äôm a warrior, i‚Äôve lost 23 pounds and counting, and i live life day by day. i hope to eventually travel around the world, telling boys and girls my story and to let them know that they shouldn‚Äôt feel guilty and hate themselves like i did for so long. he didn‚Äôt silence me. he just made my voice louder! @blogilates @popflex_active #iamapowergirl

shame üòîüíî rp @casperhilt (non graphic. sound onüîä) i did this footage a couple of days ago, tuesday, feb. 5th at aarhus slaughterhouse in denmark.
it shows the unloading from the trucks of spend and worn out dairy cows send to slaughter. killed because the quality of their breast milk is faling after 2-4 years of constant forced milking and pregnancies.
you can tell they are skin and bones, all their nutrients went straight to their forced overproduction of milk. they look like cows dying of old age (age 20-25), but they¬¥re most likely only 3-6 years old.

please notice the 'downer' left behind in the truck (aprox. 0:50), standard procedure is that she will be killed when all the other cows are dead, because 'downers' are considered 'cumbersome' , the slaughterhouse workers told me that earlier last year. - a 'downer' is the dairy industry¬¥s term used for a collapsed dairy cow who can not stand on her own legs anymore.

got milk? - or got basic, moral standards?

text:
still i remained silent!
the mask i wore felt like second skin! you see after a while you get so used to wearing a mask, you forget to take it off because its comforting, you control what people see and hear.  in your own twisted way, you think you have confidence and control hiding behind a mask. what is the cost of silence.  your inner peace, joy and health.  no more silence.  i will say what i truly feel at the risk of hurting those close to me.  it doesn't matter if i'm called judgemental, critical, negative and a host of names but one thing i do know, it's my heart's truth.  what i'm truly thinking and feeling. if i hurt you, i hurt you but i will not remain silent again.  i'm not competing in a popularity contest.  i will not tell you what you want to hear but what you need to hear! they say what goes around comes around.  so if i set out to deliberately hurt you with my response, remember karma is a bitch! the eye sees everything.

text:
wring it out, scratch the surface, erase it away. 
there are things i need to write about with this drawing, but i don‚Äôt have the words yet‚Äîjust the sensation of them, sitting in my mouth, not fully formed but wanting to be said. 
yesterday i felt a constant and electric anxiety, buzzing just beneath the surface. a frantic energy. i thought, perhaps, it had to do with my lengthy list of to do‚Äôs...but as i was driving with the radio chatter going, the source of it broke open; it‚Äôs this time of year, nearly ten years ago, that i was assaulted. on the radio a woman talked about the governor of virginia should resign, but how the lieutenant governor(now facing several assault allegations) should be given a fair investigation. 
fair. i don‚Äôt know what that means. i know i thought the world worked one way before my assault, but was crushed by a very different reality. i was crushed that another person could do that to me. i was crushed that the police officer blamed me for my assault and subsequently wrote a callous report. i was crushed that the spd did nothing, that friends abandoned me, that my rapist could just leave without any repercussions. i don‚Äôt know a single survivor that has had a fair or just trial or investigation. 
it is hard to process and move past trauma when you live in a culture that keeps perpetuating it. i don‚Äôt have a hopeful note to end this on right now‚Äîi am tired. .
.
.
.

text:
@moyenyen brings #womensauthorexchange a story about the struggles of a young woman, including her relationship with her mother and her friends. ******************* this book explores a time in the life of tise, a young and beautiful girl, her love for modelling and her near death experience. it talks about the strained relationship between tise and her mum and how no matter how much tise strived to please her mum, she never seemed to do enough. it also explores friendship in its pure state between tise and her friend chichi. ''not all heroes wear capes,'' but this wasn't revealed till the book's end. it also addressed other topics that are not freely discussed but is beginning to gain attention in the african society, topics like depression and suicide. to read, kindly click link in bio and first two chapters are free for download in bio as well. also available on amazon.

#womensfiction #womenauthotchallenge #shortstory #thriller #suspence #danger #storyteller#moyindastoryteller #moyenyen#natheworkweywedeydo #writing #storytelling#screenwriting #scriptwriting #writersofinstagram #ebook #novel #africanbooks #africanbooklover #proudlyafrican #proudlynigerian #metoo #metoomovement #girlchild #motherslove

text:
revered as a civil rights icon, rosa parks is best known for sparking the 1955 montgomery bus boycott, but her activism in the black community predates that day. she joined the national association for the advancement of colored people (naacp) in 1943, 12 years before that fateful commute. in her first years in the organization, she worked specifically on criminal justice and its application in alabama communities.
one part of this was protecting black men from false accusations and lynchings; the other was ensuring that black people who had been sexually assaulted by white people could get their day in court. this particular issue was close to parks‚Äô heart as in 1931 a white male neighbor had attempted to assault her. #blackhistorymonth #blackexcellence #blackwomen #blacklivesmatter #metoo

text:
7/26 weeks of feminism! welcome back to feminist friday! this week we have an old friend of mine from unm, sila. she wrote a powerful poem on her meaning of feminism and it‚Äôs perfectüå∏ excited for you to read!!
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
‚Äúit is a struggle,

a struggle to prove a point

a struggle for a fight, but less violent

and the worst part is

trying to show other women,

that feminism is not

hating men

or

hating at all

it is sharing

sharing everything.

it is

equality

for all,

not just women.

feminism is a constant

peaceful fight

for just the same thing he has. they have.

all we want, all i want

is solely what you have

without having to work hard

and gain things like

money, respect, and time.

i want it as you have it,

naturally.

privilege.

why can't we all be privileged?

i want them to see

that this is all i want

to be equal

to be treated,

seen,

observed,

considered,

and heard

the same way they do him and them.‚Äù

text:
in the first time in two years, 2 months and 2 weeks, i got a gym membership.  it feels awkward and foreign to even hear those words coming out of my mouth, me who lives for endorphins and sweat, without my church for this long.  but lots of things since my assault 27 months ago have felt awkward and foreign.  like a lab rat, i‚Äôve watched over myself and its effects time and time again that have revealed themselves post trauma.  believe me when i say it‚Äôs been illuminating. but, that‚Äôs what the dark gives us, a place to discover our light again.

in many ways, i have felt hijaked with a heightened sense of fear and anxiety blurring the lines of my reality.  it took me a long time again to feel comfortable leaving my home, not what i was expecting upon moving to nyc.  even my part-time job felt a little easier to interview  for because i knew the route, it was across the street from my husband‚Äôs gym.  a sense of safety and trust in my environment and in myself was something i had to relearn again.  so was self worth and love.

as i say these words, i see how far i let myself shrink, sometimes not even realizing how far i had taken to disappearing from the things that were most important to me, as if taking up as little space as possible would offer protection, or a guarantee of love. 
yet, when we don‚Äôt ask for the things we need in small ways, we begin to act out in bigger ways.  i began reaching for the lowest hanging fruit to cope with the aftermath and my spirals. it hasn‚Äôt always been pretty. 
but, things are beginning to make sense again. my path coming back in to focus, the pillars of my leap method still standing strong amidst the fog, and  i am excited by what i am experiencing and can see now.  i am excited to share this journey and what i‚Äôve also gained through my training in the ‚Äúspironess method‚Äù , a breathing method that reprograms your parasympathetic nervous system, last summer in france.  in a deeper level, the breath teaches us to receive. 
i‚Äôm happy to be cracked open again, as if awakened from a dream.  a part of this due to the loved ones closest to me.  truth is something my tribe lives by. ** rest in comments.  #metoo #spironess

text:
sexual assaults at military academies are on the rise.  the number of *reported* sexual assaults was up just slightly last year over the year before.  but what's worse: an anonymous survey revealed that the number of students who said they had been the victim of unwanted sexual contact was was up by more than 50%. so, it's happening more often and victims are even less likely to report their sexual assault.  these statistic reflect what we see in the civilian world as well - the number of unreported cases far outnumbers those that are reported, and victims are reluctant to come forward.  this keeps the abhorrent behavior in the shadows and leads to more and more victims.  our service women and men deserve better.‚†Ä
. . .‚†Ä
from the article: "after a decade-plus of concerted efforts to address sexual harassment and assault, the problem has only gotten worse," said jackie speier, the california democrat who led the hearing of the military personnel subcommittee. "this isn't a blip, a 'me too' bump, or some accident. it's a clear illustration of a destructive trend and systemic problem."‚†Ä
. . .‚†Ä
(story & üì∏by @npr: despite prevention programs, sexual assaults rise at military academies https://buff.ly/2tnudcz)‚†Ä
. . .‚†Ä
#hruprise #metoo #timesup #military #usaf #usafacademy #navy #navalacademy #army #westpoint #sexualassault
name: HRuprise

text:
finished the care and feeding of ravenously hungry girls last night and woke up thinking about it this morning. will be posting my thoughts in the next few days! in the meantime, i thought i‚Äôd finally post my review of stay up with hugo best by erin somers, which is out in april.

june bloom is a 29-year old aspiring comedy writer living in new york. she‚Äôs broke, she‚Äôs tired, and she‚Äôs just found out that the late night show she works for ‚Äì the one featuring her aging idol, hugo best ‚Äì is letting her, hugo, and the rest of the staff go. when hugo finds june doing stand-up at a drab comedy club that offers a complimentary hot dog with every drink, he invites her to his mansion in connecticut for memorial day weekend. june accepts because, well, what does she have to lose?

between the #metoo and #timesup movements, every bit of me believed this book was going to go in one direction, and it‚Äôs not that it went the opposite way, somers just took an entirely different path. and after finishing this novel, it‚Äôs clear that it was the best one.

like @michellereadsbooks writes, this book is a character study of these two sad, sometimes unlikeable, but relatable leads who spend a weekend skirting around self-destructive behaviors. despite their 30+ year age gap, june and hugo both find themselves confronting the same question: what does it mean to make it? which is a question that goes beyond the page, one that‚Äôs sure to resonate with the reader because of the culture we currently live in.

relevant, witty, and sprinkled with humor, stay up with hugo best is a must-read.

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign‚Äôs use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there ‚Äúcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating‚Äù. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday‚Äôs hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon

throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign‚Äôs use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there ‚Äúcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating‚Äù. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday‚Äôs hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
french media in crisis as they face their own #metoo moment | world news
#
florence desruol was a freelance consultant living in lyon when the attacks began in 2009. hundreds of abusive messages were posted online, a false account was created in her name, and her head was photoshopped on to pornograph images and published. ‚Äúi was called a slut, a whore, my face was grafted on to a picture of a naked woman having sex ‚Äì it was all designed to humiliate and silence me,‚Äù she said. what stood out was that the abuse was coming from a group of young, influential journalists in paris, many at the heart of prominent newsrooms and websites. about 30 men, several of whom were working for progressive or left-leaning media, had started a ‚Äúboys‚Äô club‚Äù called the ligue du lol (league of lol). they are accused of running online harassment campaigns against feminists, female journalists, writers of colour and gay people ‚Äì often using false accounts to spread racist and sexist abuse and rape-threats. the french media were thrown into crisis this week when the full scale of abuse began to emerge. it has been deemed french media‚Äôs #metoo moment. ‚Äúthey were the twitter stars of the moment, they seemed untouchable, but i took them on,‚Äù‚Ä¶

text:
anna pauline "pauli" murray was an american civil rights activist who became a lawyer, a women's rights activist, episcopal priest, and author. after earning a master's degree in law at university of california, berkeley, she became the first african american to receive a doctor of juridical science degree from yale law school.
üî∂
as a lawyer, murray argued for civil rights and women's rights. naacp chief counsel thurgood marshall called murray's 1950 book, "states' laws on race and color", the "bible" of the civil rights movement. murray served on the 1961‚Äì1963 presidential commission on the status of women, being appointed by john f. kennedy. in 1966, she was a co-founder of the national organization for women. ruth bader ginsburg named murray as a co-author of a brief on the 1971 case reed v. reed, in recognition of her pioneering work on gender discrimination. this case articulated the "failure of the courts to recognize sex discrimination for what it is and its common features with other types of arbitrary discrimination."
üî∂
drawn to the ministry in 1977, murray became the first african american woman to be ordained as an episcopal priest, in the first year that any women were ordained by that church.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

never forget. . (2016)
chicago police chase an unarmed black teen, whom they say was in a stolen car, into a backyard on the southside of chicago. 
the teen tries to hop the fence and is shot several times in the back by a cop. 
the officer jumps on him, handcuffs and roughs him up while screaming stop resisting, while the teen was dead.. he then kicked the body yelling "bitch ass mother fu@##&r..
the officers then get their stories together with the supervisor while giving hi-fives to each other. 
all of the above is caught on camera with audio and video.

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
legacy_of_late dromotoyeoyetunde ‚òÜ legacy to impact lives ‚òÜ

allotment of part of his will to underprivileged became fulfilled today. family observed a year's celebration of life.

as valentine's being celebrated across the world, we are celebrating legacy of late dr_omotoye_oyetunde. 
he passed at this time last year to glory in the usa. blessing many as he made provisions in his will to allot a particular percentage of his asset to underprivileged in nigeria, africa 
so today, 12 boxes of clothes and other wares including shoes were shipped  from the usa handing over to wheels of hope rising foundation by engineer kumolu olumide and team on behalf of the his family (wife: pamela e. omotoye (nee bitts) and children: eiren denzel and jadesola) these are being donated to people living with disabilities in lagos and ogun state, nigeria.

we are so grateful for his legacy. this is why we are celebrating this man of passion for underprivileged. we challenge everyone out there to take action to impact lives without discrimination through sharing of humanity. 
be a part of this event and watch as we donate this items to underprivileged by  restoring their hope. by getting designers wares to put on. due to courtesy of late_dromotoyeoyetunde, we are always ready to scale up our impact with your support and partnership

text:
i‚Äôm laying on the floor of the closet, tucked as far back as i can be, with tears streaming down my cheeks. screaming silently inside myself, i cannot stop my body from shaking or the room from spinning. the door is locked, but i know he can come in if he wants to. he‚Äôs already told me he can. still, it‚Äôs the only sense of safety i can give myself. it‚Äôs the only place i feel i have to go.

at some point i‚Äôll stop crying. i‚Äôll disappear so far inside myself that my limbs get cold and the stillness becomes palpable. because screaming silent screams and swallowing endless sobs? eventually, your body just grabs anything left of you and tucks it all away.

have you ever screamed a silent scream as ‚Äòloudly‚Äô as you can? it‚Äôs a special kind of awful that leaves a special kind of scar.

i had no one to turn to because the ones i tried to share with couldn‚Äôt hear me. they would brush my feelings off as my attachment style or my inability to stay in a relationship. they would tell me i was loved and that love is all that we can ask for. or they wouldn‚Äôt acknowledge my words at all. leaving me with a silence that made me question myself, my experience, and whether i even spoke in the first place.

it‚Äôs not normal to scream silent screams. to have sobs so deep and painful that swallowing them makes your throat close up... actually, literally, physically. it‚Äôs not normal for the world to start spinning and your body to shake in terror.

never let anyone else tell you what‚Äôs true for you. never let their silence or inability to listen and hear the obvious make you feel like the crazy, messed up one. and never, ever let them explain you, your experience, or your feelings away.

some people are hiding from their own demons and simply can't show up for you. some people have already made a decision about you and the situation that they simply can't go against, because 'knowing' is the only thing they have. and some people are just the kind of people you don't need in your life at all.

but there are other people... people who will hear what you're trying to say when you can't even hear yourself anymore.

text:
not all princes are bred to be kind.
some are molded into their fathers,
some are made into stone.
look at their throne carefully,
open your eyes to see,
some of these boys do not turn into men,
they turn into broken dreams.
.
.

i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
without wasting anymore time feeling guilty for having kept this to myself and a few close people, i'm gonna relate this tale. 
i was 12, bullied straight up for three years, alone, not a single friend, just a guy who i'd talk to here and there. imagine me, someone who can't stop talking, not having talked much straight for a thousand days. well, this guy was 14 and now that i think about it, manipulated me into dating him. 2 years make a huge difference to maturity and i'm sure he knew what he was doing. we dated for 5 months before he broke it off to date someone else. here's where it gets interesting : after the break up, he took advantage of my emotionally fragile state and started touching me inappropriately. this continued for months. when i tried telling the girl he was dating, he dismissed me off as an attention seeker. he had my facebook password and started talking to people portraying a picture of me being obsessed with him. imagine having just one friend for four years and they go ahead and do this. nobody believed me. i still don't know what i did to deserve it. i've forgiven him but i've developed a fear of being isolated, falsely accused and abandoned. it's where my insecurities stem from. his exact parting words were, "you're crazy to think anyone would want you for anything other than sexual favors."
_
_
_
i am 19, and i still get scared of people misunderstanding and spreading false rumors about me.  seek therapy. it's not too late. not for me. not for you. we didn't deserve what happened to us but we also don't deserve what we're doing to ourselves. don't let these events control your life.

text:
our ideals speak beyond the logo that you see. our trademark distill as motivating feelings into the lives of people we interact with daily, saturating our space with positivity. the payoff is fabulous enough to inspire devotion to humanitarian causes. 
our key actions are:

leadership development

we have realized that women leaders must be in a continual process of leadership development to attain their full potential. we provide experiential leadership development opportunities for women.

impact

we believe that making impact is proof of leadership effectiveness. we are sold out to service and also provide opportunities for women leaders to take action or participate in global development.

connecting women

one of our most effective tools for women leadership development has been networking. we provide women opportunities to connect, and develop profitable relationships. our chapters' support-system-framework has been a potent model for this.

join this movement in kigali via awlo.org/awlc

i have a secret.

that meant something dark when i was little.

as a survivor of abuse, i learned that not everyone will believe your story.

as an author, i've learned to write "happily ever after", even if it's not.

granted, i have a wonderful partner and a gorgeous son, but there's a glacial cavern inside me where noc, the black wolf who leaves no tracks, resides.

my secret is this: i'm writing noc's story and, to an extent, my own. i'm calling it a "biographical folk lore" and it's a tale i'm hesitant to share.

judgement, real or imagined, is something most survivors fear. this project allows me to wrap my bitter core of truth inside the buffer of fiction. 
my experience has been discredited. conspiracy against me by those i trusted and loved destroyed any chance i had at legal justice. i rarely share my past, not because it is raw, but because the judgement, the doubt, isn't worth it.

you, my readers, can believe or discredit at your whim. the choice, something i was never given, will be yours.

dedicated to my pack of survivors: petra and the wolf, coming 2020.

text:
thao & the get down stay down, a man alive (2016). this amazing fourth record from the san francisco alternative folk group tell‚Äôs the story of thao nguyen‚Äôs relationship with the father who abandoned her.  she also addresses sexual assault and abuses of power, right on the heels of the #metoo movement and the election of an admitted sexual abuser in the white house. these are some of her most powerful and vulnerable lyrics, yet the music is upbeat and full of danceable grooves, most likely the product of the amazing production by merrill garbus (tune-yards). this was high on my list of best records from 2016 and probably one of my favorite releases in the last ten years.

text:
my (mystical and male) #metoo perspective:

part 1: ‚Äúwillful suffering‚Äù

i do not know the experience of being raped in this body, but i have explored my strong feminine aspects (my astrological natal chart is 80% feminine) and in the process have attuned to the feminine frequency of collective consciousness. 
for instance, through a shamanic medicine journey i have glimpsed through the eyes of a virgin slave girl gang-raped to death. i lived horror. 
i felt sorrow, and i believed at the time that the best way to empathize was to feel even deeper sorrow. i unintentionally took on the task of collective healing and processing.. and it has almost broken me.

shockingly, suffering vicariously for others provided an emotional escape. it provided an addictive substitute to my own insecurities. it became an excuse to turn away from my own personal challenges and responsibilities.

combined with my life circumstances and obsessive thought patterns, the suffering stirred a perfect storm of depression and anxiety that has almost consumed me to death.

one day a few wise friends reminded me that collective processing is not my obligation, nor a path to salvation. other people‚Äôs‚Äô soul paths are not within my jurisdiction. i realized that this extends not just to other people with different experiences than me, but also to other people with similar experiences. in other words, i don‚Äôt have to carry the pain of everyone who are suffering my own afflictions, either. i don‚Äôt have to stay in the perception of victimhood. i can literally redefine myself. i am not beholden to a story. i need not feel guilt for rising out of the suffering. this is not to say that we can just ‚Äúsnap out of‚Äù trauma, but rather that we often get in our own way of healing by unnecessarily carrying the pain of others.

for most of my life i have empathized with those who suffer (including my own past selves) to the point of orbiting dangerously close to the event horizon of darkness and death.

i am now more conscious of this pattern, and i realize the potential for others to become more conscious of it too. we can break out of our past. (continued below...)

for instance, through a shamanic medicine journey i have glimpsed through the eyes of a virgin slave girl gang-raped to death. i lived horror. 
i felt sorrow, and i believed at the time that the best way to empathize was to feel even deeper sorrow. i unintentionally took on the task of collective healing and processing.. and it has almost broken me.

shockingly, suffering vicariously for others provided an emotional escape. it provided an addictive substitute to my own insecurities. it became an excuse to turn away from my own personal challenges and responsibilities.

combined with my life circumstances and obsessive thought patterns, the suffering stirred a perfect storm of depression and anxiety that has almost consumed me to death.

one day a few wise friends reminded me that collective processing is not my obligation, nor a path to salvation. other people‚Äôs‚Äô soul paths are not within my jurisdiction. i realized that this extends not just to other people with different experiences than me, but also to other people with similar experiences. in other words, i don‚Äôt have to carry the pain of everyone who are suffering my own afflictions, either. i don‚Äôt have to stay in the perception of victimhood. i can literally redefine myself. i am not beholden to a story. i need not feel guilt for rising out of the suffering. this is not to say that we can just ‚Äúsnap out of‚Äù trauma, but rather that we often get in our own way of healing by unnecessarily carrying the pain of others.

for most of my life i have empathized with those who suffer (including my own past selves) to the point of orbiting dangerously close to the event horizon of darkness and death.

i am now more conscious of this pattern, and i realize the potential for others to become more conscious of it too. we can break out of our past. (continued below...)

text:
although 117  official  reports of sexual assault were reported in 2017-2018, 747 military academy students said they received unwanted sexual contact. a 50% increase in two years. of the cases reported only 9 were prosecuted with only 1 conviction. that is literally less than a 1% conviction rate for reported cases. and less than a 0.13% conviction rate if including all cases. 
if this was a prosecutor‚Äôs success rate they‚Äôd be fired
a sales exec
a doctor
a dog walker.
you see my point?

you have higher odds of getting into harvard
of being in new jersey
of dying in the next 12 months
of being audited by the irs

the abuse of power and assault of womxn specifically by military systems is long standing and documented. it should come as no surprise that these systems would be unable (unwilling) to administer justice when challenged internally.
but make no mistake: this is unacceptable. and the men and womxn who choose to put their lives at risk deserve better.

text: for years i stayed silent. i wouldn't say a word. i wasn't the one who told, but once it was out, i wanted to scream about it from the roof tops. yet, i still stayed silent. i refused help, and instead decided i could manage on my own. i had used education as a safety blanket. i spent elementary school going in early and helping my teachers set up, and i spent middle and high school hanging out in hallways with other students who had no where else to be. in college, i finally started telling people about what had happened. a simple statement, "i was sexually assaulted for eight years." the statement sometimes came easy as if it was nothing out of the ordinary and a simple thing to move beyond, but other times it rocked me hard and i'd cry while baring a bit of my soul. post college, i don't tend to simply tell who ever will listen in person, but rather share when i feel it contributes to the relationship or topic at hand. not many folks  in my life know my story. they see the drive i have and the desire to learn. they see the achievements i have and mischaracterize me. i recently had an acquaintance tell me how ignorant and privileged i was simply disagreeing with them. i didn't tell them i wasn't, but rather that their characterization of me is disappointing since i felt as though i had lived through some deep traumas and used education as a way to push forward through them. they never responded. i can't control other people, but i can choose to how i respond to people and things that occur in life. i chose to respond to christ by saying, "yes lord, i believe in you and trust you." by staying that, i also seek to follow his word and share all that he's done in my life. christ is the reason i was able to make it through the abuse. he is the reason i desire to share my life. not so that i may be seen, but that his goodness may be seen in me. i am broken, but christ calls me whole. he sees my soul and thought, "i'm willing to die for her." and then he did so that i may stand justified before god and called a daughter of the king most high. a friend once told me i wear my story like armor. i couldn't agree more. the very thing intended to destroy me strengthened me

text:
this is ana mendieta, a cuban-american refugee who became a beloved performance artist. she died in 1985 at the age of just 36, possibly murdered by her husband of 8 months carl andre who was a famous sculptor. the only witness to her falling to her death was her husband and he kept changing his story which made it difficult to gather evidence and investigate at the time. it's thought that she might have been pushed out of the window as she and her husband had been arguing hours earlier. ultimately, he was tried and acquitted due to lack of evidence plus he went for a no jury trial. she was portrayed as a hard drinking, tempestuous latina woman. just years later in 1992, carl held an exhibition which was met by feminist protests. 
this is not a unique thing, many important men have got away with horrific crimes and many more have been suspected but due to their influence, have managed to suppress accusations or frighten victims into silence. still more have not had their careers destroyed by allegations, carl certainly didn't despite being the number one suspect in a possible murder. this is why i'll never worry for the careers of famous people accused of rape, sexual abuse, domestic violence, spousal abuse without physical violence and more. 
many stars of the classic rock era raped "baby groupies" like sable starr. elvis literally married a young teenage girl. donald trump himself was best friends with jeffrey eppstein, an actual child molester and the pair of them allegedly raped a 13 year old. 
i just don't buy it when someone frets that their favourite star will have his career ruined by allegations (to be clear, i'm not interested in discussing instances where women have done terrible things as that is off topic for this particular post). you can literally get away with murder or rape if you have the influence and money. false allegations are terrible, yes, but many of those are rooted in racism and that is also something for another discussion. so i post this because many people who do mean well have expressed concerns for their favourite celebrities being accused of harassment or rape. #feminism #politics #metoo #abuse

text:
i am a failure, a total disaster.
from a lonely childhood to a boring job, a failed marriage and even my womb is weak. every single day of my life been a struggle, how many times i was wondering do i really need to battle each day to be able to survive the next day. my life is bitter, when i go to sleep, i am praying to not wake up. each morning when the alarm goes off, i see a zombie, a walking zombie unable to find his place in this world. i even failed to kill myself. this is a common feeling that most of us had felt at least once in our life but some people go beyond that feeling, so please remember you are not on your own, reach for help. we all went through something.

text:
announcing my next family constellation workshop in kolkata on saturday, 23rd feb.
.
.
as we unravel the entanglements within our family dynamics and honor and acknowledge our lineage, we create calm ripples into the present, into ourselves, our families and our communities. .
.
family constellations create a window for us to do this, get a hidden paradigm behind our problems and much more. .
.
participants describe this form of healing as deeply transformative, intense and extremely potent.
.
.
.
to register pls call: 9830 897 052
.
.
venue: jodhpur park, kolkata
slot 1: 10am -1pm
slot 2: 2pm - 5pm

dm for registrations.
one is welcome and encouraged to stay for both slots for maximim impact.
.
very very limited seats. so pls register fast if self work is your thing.
.
.
.
>> issues that are explored in this workshop:
‚Ä¢ anxiety & depression
‚Ä¢ love & relationships ‚Ä¢ physical issues ‚Ä¢ missing sense of connection & purpose
‚Ä¢ challenging relationships ‚Ä¢ effects of traumas
‚Ä¢ problems in work environments ‚Ä¢ dealing with a difficult fate or illness
‚Ä¢ fears & phobias 
eg: fear of success/failure
‚Ä¢ feeling stuck & unable to move forward in life. ‚Ä¢ emotional & physical issues
‚Ä¢ impact of violence on the family .
.
.........................................................
.
.

full day (including lunch & tea):
5,500/- participants
4,500/- observers

one slot (including tea):
4,500/- for participants
3,500/- for observers
.
*participants : address an issue .
*observers : watch, as well as step in as representatives of other client's family members or other elements. and receive an equal amount of personal revelations and deep healing, even if they don't directly address their own issue.
.
.
.
